text_Original: It really is fascinating how it can capture those micro-expressions (especially as Lex/Mark discussed at 11:00). That could really help with immersion for use-cases where NO AVATAR is required. The question then becomes WHICH elements can translate toward avatars (likely just eye, mouth, etc). Then one wonders if users would even WANT their expressions to be tracked at all times. If you were in a social setting, you might NOT want to blush, appear angry, look sad, grin too much, etc. There are instances when appearing neutral would be a benefit. Perhaps a series of toggles for expression rendering.
